  1. Question

    An ellipse is the set of (\(x\), \(y\)) points that satisfy the equation below.

    \[\frac{(x-h)^2}{(r_1)^2}+\frac{(y-k)^2}{(r_2)^2}=1\]

    where the center is \((h,k)\), the horizontal radius is \(r_1\), and the vertical radius is \(r_2\).

    Determine the parameters of the ellipse in the graph below. You can assume all parameters are integers.


    • \(h=\)
    • \(k=\)
    • \(r_1=\)
    • \(r_2=\)

    Which of the following equations would give the graph above?

    \[\begin{align} A&:~~\frac{(x+2)^2}{16}+\frac{(y+3)^2}{25}=1 & B&:~~\frac{(x+2)^2}{16}+\frac{(y-3)^2}{25}=1 & C&:~~\frac{(x-2)^2}{16}+\frac{(y+3)^2}{25}=1 & D&:~~\frac{(x-2)^2}{16}+\frac{(y-3)^2}{25}=1 \\ E&:~~\frac{(x+3)^2}{16}+\frac{(y+2)^2}{25}=1 & F&:~~\frac{(x+3)^2}{16}+\frac{(y-2)^2}{25}=1 & G&:~~\frac{(x-3)^2}{16}+\frac{(y+2)^2}{25}=1 & H&:~~\frac{(x-3)^2}{16}+\frac{(y-2)^2}{25}=1 \\ I&:~~\frac{(x+2)^2}{25}+\frac{(y+3)^2}{16}=1 & J&:~~\frac{(x+2)^2}{25}+\frac{(y-3)^2}{16}=1 & K&:~~\frac{(x-2)^2}{25}+\frac{(y+3)^2}{16}=1 & L&:~~\frac{(x-2)^2}{25}+\frac{(y-3)^2}{16}=1 \\ M&:~~\frac{(x+3)^2}{25}+\frac{(y+2)^2}{16}=1 & N&:~~\frac{(x+3)^2}{25}+\frac{(y-2)^2}{16}=1 & O&:~~\frac{(x-3)^2}{25}+\frac{(y+2)^2}{16}=1 & P&:~~\frac{(x-3)^2}{25}+\frac{(y-2)^2}{16}=1 \\ \end{align}\]

    Equation



    Solution


    So: \[\begin{align} h &= -2\\\\ k &= 3\\\\ r_1 &= 4\\\\ r_2 &= 5 \end{align}\]

    Substitute those numbers into the equation:

    \[\frac{(x+2)^2}{16}+\frac{(y-3)^2}{25}=1\]
